<div id="review_3713079468" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3713079468" />
    <a title="Neal Adolph" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5459072-neal-adolph"><img alt="Neal Adolph" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1313534109p2/5459072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3713079468?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neal Adolph" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neal Adolph" href="/user/show/5459072-neal-adolph">Neal Adolph</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=writers-of-colour">writers-of-colour</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=south-american">south-american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=2021-reads">2021-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5459072-neal-adolph?shelf=nobel-prize">nobel-prize</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3713079468" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15018939794734356645">This novel was not the novel I thought it was. I don&apos;t mean that in anything other than the most literal sense. When I took this down from my shelf it was part of a bundle of very specific emotions that I was looking for. I was feeling nostalgic for Colombia, a country that I have lived in, a place where I nearly fell in love, and the one part of the world where I have ever felt the full disempowerment of being an outsider. It was also where my imagination became unlocked, and my creative desire</span>
  <span id="freeText15018939794734356645" style="display:none">This novel was not the novel I thought it was. I don't mean that in anything other than the most literal sense. When I took this down from my shelf it was part of a bundle of very specific emotions that I was looking for. I was feeling nostalgic for Colombia, a country that I have lived in, a place where I nearly fell in love, and the one part of the world where I have ever felt the full disempowerment of being an outsider. It was also where my imagination became unlocked, and my creative desires developed a power that I hadn't felt since high school. It was a space of experimentation and joy and experience.<br /><br />So it was surely only be the slip of my hand that I took down The Autumn of the Patriarch and not my intended reading target, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23884.The_General_in_His_Labyrinth" title="The General in His Labyrinth by Gabriel García Márquez" rel="nofollow noopener">The General in His Labyrinth</a>. I thought The General would be the right book for right then, the end of December and final days of a Trump's presidency, mixed in with a bit of magical realness, and adding in the sense of isolation and frustration that was emmanating from the oval office with such force that even up here, on Canada's western coast, it could be felt in the air like a incomfortably warm, angry old breeze.<br /><br />I didn't realize I had made the error for a few pages, but the mistake was one of those "for better or worse" moments that we all get in our reading lives. By then I had been once again convinced that Garcia Marquez is, or was, one of the most exceptional authors of the twentieth century.<br /><br />Like his other novels, it is hard to sum this one up into something that can be digested by somebody who hasn't also read it. But here's an attempt. <br /><br />What we see here is the life of a dictator, told at various times by the dictator and their mother and their wife, and their body double, and his general that he roasts and feeds, and the people of his country, and for a few short comma splices the young woman from the barrio that entrances him, and then for a few long comma splices the man he imprisons for 22 years while he remembers where it is that he had seen him before, and a few other narrators here or there for glimmering thoughts. Admittedly, it is a spectacle of guesses at times. Narrators are not named, but you float into their thoughts and out of them again, without indication other than context and shifts in the point of view, and with little help from a period to make it clear that a thought had ended. It's a bit of a whirlwind.<br /><br />Through his life, we watch his supposed death a few times over, witness his grasps for power become ever more desperate, watch as his tricks begin to trick himself, how he loses his sense of reality from the beginning to an ending, when he buckles under senility and a lifetime lived in magic and cruelty. We watch him take land from the church, fall in love with a nun who becomes his wife, watch him give the land back to the church. Before that we watch his mother die, which surprised me if only because she seemed, like the dictator, as though she would live forever; but die, she does, with only her son to be able to care for him. Before that we watch him fall in love with a young citizen of his state who enraptures him with a simple rose, and well after that we see his presence get felt in a balcony during a poetry show during which he watches the true elegance of a being that can capture the full attention of the audience. Rivers run the wrong way on order. The sea disappears as though it can be owned. Clocks rewind or jump forward. <br /><br />It is, in total, a story of decline and suffering for a people who are caught up in the cruel power-hungry games of an emperor who imagines himself judge, and also for a man who discovers, over time, his own illusion of control has been used against him. That is, he might be the one who discovers it. The be fair it isn't always clear who the narrator is. But even if he isn't the one who discovers it, somebody does, and they take the reader along for the final pages and into the universe of wisdom that opens up as, finally, the Patriarch actually dies.<br /><br />So, just as well for that mistake in the book I grabbed, I suppose. This one proved to meet a lot of my needs and exceed all of my expectations. May 2021 come with a great many more mistakes as incendiary and exciting as this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15018939794734356645" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


