  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1062407605" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1062407605" />
    <a title="Louise" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9281934-louise"><img alt="Louise" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1336194494p2/9281934.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1062407605?book_show_action=true">Sep 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Louise" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Louise" href="/user/show/9281934-louise">Louise</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9281934-louise?shelf=south-america-fic-lit">south-america-fic-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9281934-louise?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9281934-louise?shelf=nobel-prize-winning-author">nobel-prize-winning-author</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1062407605" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9860241783164975436">This is the most powerful GGM novel I have read. Written over 7 years from 1968 to 1975 it metaphorically condemns dictatorial powers. Rafeal Trujillo comes to mind, but there were many other (Caribbean and elsewhere) dictators of the time to inspire it and the portrait is valid today. <br/><br/>You read how the dictator treats his double, courts the most beautiful woman in the country, destroys anyone with a hint of knowledge of his ill gotten gains, marries and how his wife and son die and what is done </span>
  <span id="freeText9860241783164975436" style="display:none">This is the most powerful GGM novel I have read. Written over 7 years from 1968 to 1975 it metaphorically condemns dictatorial powers. Rafeal Trujillo comes to mind, but there were many other (Caribbean and elsewhere) dictators of the time to inspire it and the portrait is valid today. <br /><br />You read how the dictator treats his double, courts the most beautiful woman in the country, destroys anyone with a hint of knowledge of his ill gotten gains, marries and how his wife and son die and what is done about it, how he establishes a cult for his mother and more. Uday Hussein’s treatment of losing teams comes to mind as a reality that would fit this narrative well.<br /><br />The book was demanding of its writer, and equally so of the reader. Each chapter is one long paragraph. The run on sentences are so long that several times I had to backtrack to remind myself of who/what was being described or whether the time past present or future. The few periods among the many commas were very welcome. I wasted some time trying to figure out who was narrating before realizing finally that there is no one first person and that the same is true for "he" and "she" which also shift. The lack of quotation marks is easier to deal with, but adds to the difficulty.<br /><br />The imagery is brutal. Beyond the savagery of the “patriarch” (serving a general for dinner; destroying children; practicing the new electric chair as a few examples) there are scatological references, birds and animals dining on people and creepy sex. Like all GGM novels, there are recurring images, such as the many 7 month sons (reminds the reader of the 17 male children named Aurelianos, in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/320.One_Hundred_Years_of_Solitude" title="One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcí­a Márquez" rel="nofollow noopener">One Hundred Years of Solitude</a>), the comet, shad, his mother’s birds, playing dominoes (games which the patriarch must win), the undetermined age of this dictator and more.<br /><br />Woven together the images show the absolute power of the dictator to de-humanize subjects who allow him to win at all things. They, create Potamkin villages for his pleasure. When he dies, they wonder what will become of them.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the format will keep this important book from a wider audience. As it stands I can only recommended it for serious readers with an interest in GGM and/or this topic.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9860241783164975436" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

